</div></div><div class="comment" id="comment_10057"><span class="header"><a href="http://www.sparkfun.com/users/106998" class="bold">jomama</a> <span class="wide">|</span> <b>January 31, 2010 at  9:24 AM</b><img class="star" src="http://dlnmh9ip6v2uc.cloudfront.net/images/framework/icon_star_dark.gif" alt="Comment Rating" title="Comment Rating" /><strong><span id="comment_rating_10057">1</span></strong></span><br /></span><div class="body"><p>If you are getting garbage messages across serial, make sure to check that you have the right parts in your kit.  I got a 10 MHz crystal instead of the 16 MHz.  I spent way too many hours playing with fusebits and my wiring to eventually realize that my crystal wasn't 16 MHz.</p>
</div></div><div class="comment" id="comment_19289"><span class="header"><a href="http://www.sparkfun.com/users/152625" class="bold">skatefriday</a> <span class="wide">|</span> <b>October  8, 2010 at  9:32 PM</b><img class="star" src="http://dlnmh9ip6v2uc.cloudfront.net/images/framework/icon_star_dark.gif" alt="Comment Rating" title="Comment Rating" /><strong><span id="comment_rating_19289">1</span></strong></span><br /></span><div class="body"><p>As a bunch of people have said, nobody has serial ports anymore.  It would be very, very nice if some kind sould at sparkfun would update the tutorial to describe how to do this out of a usb port.</p>
</div></div><div class="comment" id="comment_20678"><span class="header"><a href="http://www.sparkfun.com/users/157312" class="bold">mbwjr12</a> <span class="wide">|</span> <b>November 10, 2010 at 11:55 AM</b><img class="star" src="http://dlnmh9ip6v2uc.cloudfront.net/images/framework/icon_star_dark.gif" alt="Comment Rating" title="Comment Rating" /><strong><span id="comment_rating_20678">1</span></strong></span><br /></span><div class="body"><p>I can confirm that this capacitor layout simply does not work for the very common (pin-compatible) max232a subsitute, the sp232acn. Connecting pins 2 and 6 via a capacitor instead of to Vcc and Ground causes very unreliable operation at 38400bps, with about one out of ten characters getting through correctly.</p>
</div></div><div class="comment" id="comment_22713"><span class="header"><a href="http://www.sparkfun.com/users/131612" class="bold">zemm</a> <span class="wide">|</span> <b>December 12, 2010 at  4:25 AM</b><img class="star" src="http://dlnmh9ip6v2uc.cloudfront.net/images/framework/icon_star_dark.gif" alt="Comment Rating" title="Comment Rating" /><strong><span id="comment_rating_22713">1</span></strong></span><br /></span><div class="body"><p>Just a side note: if you are like me and have PuTTY open 24/7, you can use this familiar tool with serial communication also. I have my Bus Pirate, Adruino and FTDI-breakout in saved sessions along with linux servers.</p>
